'''Jeremy V. R. Hearder''' (born late 1930s) is an [[Australia]]n author and historian, and former [[diplomat]] and public servant.

He was Australia's first high commissioner to [[Zimbabwe]] (1980 to 1984) and is the author of the biography ''Jim Plim: Ambassador Extraordinary'' (released 2015).

== Life and career ==
Born in the late 1930s, Hearder was the son of one of three founders of the [[Australian Secret Intelligence Service]], former British army officer Roblin Hearder.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/lifting-the-cloak-on-spies-like-us-20120719-22czn.html|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax Media|date=20 July 2012|title=Lifting the cloak on spies like us|first=Daniel|last=Flitton|archivedate=11 June 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611060149/http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/lifting-the-cloak-on-spies-like-us-20120719-22czn.html}}</ref> The younger Hearder joined the [[Department of External Affairs (1921–70)|Department of External Affairs]] in January 1959.<ref>{{cite interview|first=Jeremy|last=Hearder|interviewer=Alice Garner|date=26 November 2009|title=Fulbright scholars oral history project}}</ref><ref name=Fijiappoint>{{cite news|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/126992283|title=New envoy to Fiji|date=1 May 1984|page=3|newspaper=The Canberra Times}}</ref>

In 1980, Hearder was appointed the first High Commissioner to Zimbabwe, shortly after Zimbabwe's independence.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id%3A%22media/pressrel/HPR10028900%22 |title=High Commissioner in Zimbabwe |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611052746/http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p%3Bquery%3DId%3A%22media/pressrel/HPR10028900%22 |archivedate=11 June 2016 |date=21 April 1980 |author=[[Department of Foreign Affairs (Australia)|Department of Foreign Affairs]] |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> Retaining his High Commissioner position, in 1981 Hearder was accredited High Commissioner to Botswana,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/127064225|title=Botswana status|date=14 August 1981|page=3|newspaper=The Canberra Times}}</ref> and in 1982 he was accredited also as Australia's first Ambassador to Mozambique.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/126901556|title=Mozambique|date=10 June 1982|newspaper=The Canberra Times|page=14}}</ref> In 1984, after his posting in Harare came to an end, Hearder moved to Suva, Fiji, to take up a second High Commissioner posting.<ref name=Fijiappoint/>

Hearder was Consul-General in Chicago from 1988 to 1991, responsible for promoting Australian trade and investment to America's mid-west.<ref name=NAA>{{citation|title=CA 8034: Australian Consulate-General, Chicago [United States of America]|url=http://naa12.naa.gov.au/scripts/SearchOld.asp?Number=CA+8034|publisher=National Archives of Australia|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/111975655|title=New consul-general|date=26 May 1988|page=3|newspaper=The Canberra Times}}</ref>

In 2015, Hearder launched his book, ''Jim Plim: Ambassador Extraordinary'', a biography of diplomat [[James Plimsoll]] whom Hearder had worked with in the late 1970s in Brussels.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.internationalaffairs.org.au/media_library/hobart-launch-of-jeremy-hearders-jim-plim-ambassador-extraordinary-a-biography-of-sir-james-plimsoll/|title=Hobart Launch of Jeremy Hearder's 'Jim Plim Ambassador Extraordinary: A biography of Sir James Plimsoll'|date=29 May 2015|publisher=Australian Institute of International Affairs|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404035828/http://www.internationalaffairs.org.au/media_library/hobart-launch-of-jeremy-hearders-jim-plim-ambassador-extraordinary-a-biography-of-sir-james-plimsoll/|archivedate=4 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/betweenthelines/the-lessons-of-a-distinguished-diplomatic-career/6654372|title=The lessons of a distinguished diplomatic career|first=Tom|last=Switzer|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Commission|date=6 August 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611053920/http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/betweenthelines/the-lessons-of-a-distinguished-diplomatic-career/6654372|archivedate=11 June 2016}}</ref> Reviewing the book, [[Philip Flood]] wrote that Hearder had done justice to Plimsoll's career as a great Australian ambassador.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/book-review-jim-plim--ambassador-extraordinary-20150519-gh2lgc.html|title=Book review: Jim Plim - Ambassador Extraordinary|first=Philip|last=Flood|author-link=Philip Flood|date=15 May 2015|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax Media|archivedate=11 June 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611054808/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/book-review-jim-plim--ambassador-extraordinary-20150519-gh2lgc.html}}</ref> The book had been 17 years in the making.<ref>{{cite speech|url=http://dfat.gov.au/news/speeches/Pages/secretarys-speech-jim-plim-ambassador-extraordinary-book-launch.aspx|title=“Jim Plim”: Ambassador Extraordinary book launch|date=14 April 2015|first=Peter|last=Varghese|author-link=Peter Varghese|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150814025435/http://dfat.gov.au/news/speeches/Pages/secretarys-speech-jim-plim-ambassador-extraordinary-book-launch.aspx|archivedate=14 August 2015}}</ref>

