{{Infobox academic | honorific_prefix = | name = Johanna Hanink | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1982 | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | region = | nationality = | period = | occupation = | title = | boards = <!-- Board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation --> | known_for = | spouse = | children = | signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = | era = | language = | discipline = [[Classics]] | sub_discipline = | movement = <!-- Should match the ideological movement or denomination (for religious), "school" of thought etc. (e.g. "Anglican", "Postmodernist", "Socialist" or "Green" etc. --> | religion = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | denomination = <!-- Religious denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | education = | alma_mater = [[Cambridge University]] | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = 2011 | school_tradition = | doctoral_advisor = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = <!--Only those with WP articles--> | main_interests = | workplaces = [[Brown University]] | notable_works = | notable_ideas = | influences = <!--Must be referenced from a third party source--> | influenced = <!--Must be referenced from a third party source--> | awards = | website = https://twitter.com/johannahan | footnotes = }}
'''Johanna Hanink''' is Associate Professor of Classics at [[Brown University]]. She specialises in [[Theatre of ancient Greece|ancient Greek theater]] and performance and the cultural life and afterlife of ancient Athens.<ref name=Brown>{{cite web |url=https://vivo.brown.edu/display/jhanink |title=Johanna Hanink |publisher=Researchers at Brown |accessdate=2017-07-15}}</ref> Hanink also serves as a contributor to [[Aeon Magazine]], the [[Chronicle for Higher Education]], and Eidolon, a scholarly publication of the [[Paideia Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hanink|first1=Johanna|title=Why Don’t More Women Write ‘Big Books’?|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/Why-Don-t-More-Women-Write/239627|website=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=2 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Johanna Hanink – EIDOLON|url=https://eidolon.pub/@johannahan|website=eidolon.pub}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Johanna Hanink - Aeon|url=https://aeon.co/users/johanna-hanink|website=Aeon|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Greek News Agenda - Rethinking Greece: Johanna Hanink on Ancients, Moderns and the politics of cultural indebtedness|url=http://www.greeknewsagenda.gr/index.php/interviews/rethinking-greece/6449-johanna-hanink|website=www.greeknewsagenda.gr|language=en-gb}}</ref>
==Career== Hanink was born in 1982 in [[Ashford, Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite web|title=02.16.2006 - Two UC Berkeley students and one alumna named Gates Cambridge Scholars|url=http://www.berkeley.edu/news/media/releases/2006/02/16_gatesscholars.shtml|website=www.berkeley.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Hanink|first1=Johanna|title=The Classical Debt: Greek Antiquity in an Era of Austerity|date=2017|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780674978300}}</ref> Hanink received her BA in Classics at the [[University of Michigan, Ann Arbor]] in 2003 and a [[Gates Scholarship]] in 2006, followed by an MA in Latin at the [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Classics student wins Gates Scholarship to study at Cambridge|url=https://record.umich.edu/articles/classics-student-wins-gates-scholarship-study-cambridge|website=The University Record}}</ref> She achieved her PhD in Classics in 2011 at [[Queens' College]], Cambridge.<ref>{{cite web|title=Johanna Hanink - Today at Brown|url=http://today.brown.edu/faculty/2010/hanink|website=today.brown.edu}}</ref>
Hanink's work focuses on Greek drama, and particularly [[Greek tragedy]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Brown professor talks on classical studies research|url=http://brandeishoot.com/2013/02/28/brown-professor-talks-on-classical-studies-research/|website=The Brandeis Hoot|date=28 February 2013}}</ref> In addition, Hanink is interested in [[Classical reception studies]] and especially the role Greek and Roman antiquity plays in modern political movements.<ref>{{cite web|title=It’s Time to Embrace Critical Classical Reception – EIDOLON|url=https://eidolon.pub/its-time-to-embrace-critical-classical-reception-d3491a40eec3|website=EIDOLON|date=1 May 2017}}</ref> Her 2017 book, ''The Classical Debt'', examines the symbolic debt of Western civilization to Greece in light of the [[Greek financial crisis]]. Hanink also writes on issues of gender in academia.<ref>{{cite web|title=More Women Classicists Need to Write Big – EIDOLON|url=https://eidolon.pub/more-women-classicists-need-to-write-big-cc1994ad1747|website=EIDOLON|date=2 March 2017}}</ref>
==Selected publications== * ''The Classical Debt: Greek Antiquity in an Era of Austerity'', [[Harvard University Press]], 2017. {{ISBN|9780674978300}}. * ''Lycurgan Athens and the Making of Classical Tragedy'', [[Cambridge University Press]], ''Cambridge Classical Studies'' series, 2014. {{ISBN|9781107062023}}. * ''Creative Lives in Classical Antiquity: Poets, Artists and Biography'', co-edited with Richard Fletcher, Cambridge University Press, ''Cambridge Classical Studies'' series, 2016. {{ISBN|9781316670651}}.
